<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="59" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,255,591]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,290,314]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">Remarks.</emphasis>
A reliable determination of this single female is impossible. It belongs to an assemblage of several moderate sized, ochraceous species (
<figureCitation box="[542,606,325,348]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1950,1974]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,1660,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,1615,1925]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. (A) Pseudothyretes kamitugensis. (B) Rhipidarctia (Hemirhipidia) postrosea. (C) Metarctia paremphares. (D) Metarctia priscilla. (E) Metarctia sp. (scale bar = 10 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206671/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
Fig. 
<number box="[592,606,325,348]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
E). The females of many species in this group remain unknown. In most cases the ascription of females to the known males is dubious and requires further researches based on extensive material. The date and collecting place of this specimen may suggest its affiliation to 
<taxonomicName box="[999,1181,394,417]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Metarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paremphares">
<emphasis box="[999,1181,394,417]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">M. paremphares</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Close comparison of morphological details of the female genitalia of the collected specimen (
<figureCitation box="[957,1023,429,452]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1295,1319]" captionTargetBox="[186,1350,239,1229]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,194,1271]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. (A – C) Rhipidarctia (Hemirhipidia) postrosea (gs S 133 (3) S 134 (Ƥ), ISEA): (A) Male genitalia. (B) Phallus. (C) Female genitalia. (D – E) Metarctia paremphares (gs S 136, ISEA): (D) Male genitalia. (E) Phallus. (F – G) Metarctia priscilla (gs S 137, ISEA): (F) Male genitalia. (G) Phallus. (H) Metarctia haematica (gs S 131, ISEA) female genitalia. (I) Metarctia sp. (gs S 139, ISEA) female genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206672/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
Fig. 
<date box="[1010,1023,429,452]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">
<number box="[1010,1023,429,452]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" value="3.0">3</number>
</date>
</figureCitation>
I) (gs - S 
<number box="[1127,1170,429,452]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" value="139.0">139</number>
, 
<collectionCode box="[1185,1246,429,452]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">ISEA</collectionCode>
) with the female 
<typeStatus box="[151,234,464,487]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">syntype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[268,442,464,487]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Metarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paremphares">
<emphasis box="[268,442,464,487]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">M. paremphares</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presented in 
<bibRefCitation author="Przybylowicz" box="[583,970,464,487]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" refString="Przybylowicz, L. (2009) Thyretini of Africa. An Illustrated Catalogue of the Thyretini (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae: Syntominae) of the Afrotropical Region. Entomonograph Series, Vol. 16, Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 170 pp." type="book" year="2009">
Przybyłowicz (
<number box="[743,801,464,487]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" value="2009.0">2009</number>
: 
<number box="[811,853,464,487]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" value="154.0">154</number>
, Plate 
<number box="[923,962,464,487]" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" value="111.0">111</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
reveals some small differences: much more distinct signum, more sclerotized basal part of ductus bursae and slightly wider, larger ostium bursae. Due to the lack of comparative material it is impossible to judge at present if these differences indicate the intraspecific variability of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Metarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paremphares">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="59">M. paremphares</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or rather represent the typical pattern of one of a few similar species.
</paragraph>
